      "message": "If you have\n\n```\nfilegroup(name \u003d \"foo\", srcs \u003d [])\nfile(name \u003d \"bar\", src \u003d \":foo\")\n```\n\nIf src is `allow_single_file\u003dTrue`, because `src` is set to a target, allow_single_file will require `:foo` to provide exactly one file. But in fact `:foo` has no files. In this case, we do not care about how many files `:foo` has. It can have 0, 1 or many. Hence we need to set `allow_files` instead.\n\nallow_single_file attributes can only contain 0 files when the attribute itself is None, e.g.\n\n```\nfile(name \u003d \"bar\", src \u003d None)\n```\n\nIn this case, allow_single_file is okay.\n\nWe can\u0027t use a filegroup instead of file because\n\n```\nfilegroup(name \u003d \"foo\", srcs \u003d [select(...)])\n```\n\nis not valid (you can\u0027t have select in lists for some reason). On the other hand, \n\n```\nfile(name \u003d \"foo\", srcs \u003d select(...))\n```\n\nis valid.",
